{{Infobox person | name = Abdelmonem Bin Eisa Alserkal | image = | caption = | birth_place = [[United Arab Emirates]] | known_for = Founder of [[Alserkal Avenue]] }}
'''Abdelmonem Bin Eisa Alserkal''' was born and raised in [[United Arab Emirates]]. After graduating from university in the United States, he began his career in real estate and development in the UAE.<ref>Boucher, Brian. [https://news.artnet.com/art-world/syrian-art-rem-koolhaass-dubai-895517 "Rem Koolhaas Infliltrates Dubai With an Expectation-Defying Art Center"] Artnet News, 17 March 2017</ref> A patron of the arts, he is the founder of [[Alserkal Avenue]], an arts hub housed in a former industrial district in the [[Al Quoz]] area of [[Dubai]]. Launched in 2007, [[Alserkal Avenue]] is home a to mix of art galleries, nonprofit spaces, restaurants, performance venues, and co-working spaces.<ref>Seaman, Anna. [http://www.thenational.ae/arts-culture/art/abdelmonem-bin-eisa-alserkal-on-the-expansion-of-dubais-alserkal-avenue "Abdelmonem bin Eisa Alserkal on the expansion of Dubai’s Alserkal Avenue"] The National, 16 June 2014.</ref>
Abdelmonem initiated an expansion of Alserkal Avenue, which was launched in early 2015. In addition to more gallery space, the expansion added a black box theatre, independent cinema, and outdoor performance venue.<ref>Jones, Kevin. [http://www.flashartonline.com/2015/07/abdelmonem-alserkal-on-the-alserkal-avenue-dubai/ "Abdelmonem Alserkal on the Alserkal Avenue / Dubai"] Flash Art, 27 July 2015. </ref> In March 2017 Abdelmonem inaugurated [[Concrete (Alserkal Avenue)]], a multipurpose venue and the first building in the UAE to be completed by the [[Office for Metropolitan Architecture]] (OMA).<ref>Gibson, Eleanor. [https://www.dezeen.com/2017/03/16/concrete-oma-cultural-events-alserkal-avenue-dubai-united-arab-emirates/ "OMA's first project in Dubai is a cultural centre with moving eight-metre-high walls"] Dezeen, 16 March 2017.</ref>
Featured in Surface magazine's 2016 Power 100 list, Abdelmonem serves on the [[British Museum]]'s Contemporary and Modern Middle Eastern Art Acquisition Group, the [[Tate]]'s Middle East and North Africa Acquisition Committee, and the [[Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation]]'s Middle Eastern Circle.<ref>Editors of Surface. [http://www.surfacemag.com/articles/power-100-list-2016-architecture-design-fashion-tech-art/ "Power 100" 1 August 2016.]</ref> Abdelmonem and the Alserkal family have been awarded the Patron of the Arts award twice, in 2012 and 2013, by HH Sheikh Mohammed Bin Rashid Al Maktoum, Vice President of the UAE and Prime Minister and Ruler of Dubai.
